<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>📖 Extra — Creating Dictionaries: Facts With Names</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> Making a Dictionary · <strong>Course:</strong> Extra Worksheet · <strong>Time:</strong> about 30 minutes</p>
<p>A list keeps things in a row, and you reach them by number. A <strong>dictionary</strong> keeps facts with <strong>names</strong>, so you reach them by name instead of counting. On paper you will read dictionary code, predict it, fix it, and explain it in your own words.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Keep these words handy: <strong>dictionary</strong>, <strong>key</strong>, <strong>value</strong>, <strong>{ }</strong>, <strong>key:value pair</strong>.</p>
</blockquote>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each snippet. Write what you think it will print.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">player = {&quot;name&quot;: &quot;Mia&quot;, &quot;level&quot;: 3}
print(player[&quot;name&quot;])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What prints? How does Python know which fact to grab?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">pet = {&quot;kind&quot;: &quot;cat&quot;, &quot;age&quot;: 2, &quot;hungry&quot;: True}
print(pet[&quot;age&quot;])
print(pet[&quot;hungry&quot;])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What two lines print?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-python">player = {&quot;name&quot;: &quot;Mia&quot;, &quot;level&quot;: 3}
print(player[&quot;score&quot;])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>There is no <code>"score"</code> key. What happens?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each snippet is broken. Read what it should do, then rewrite it so it works. Explain why the original was wrong.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — This should print the player's name. Instead it reads a number, and dictionaries are not read that way.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">player = {&quot;name&quot;: &quot;Mia&quot;, &quot;level&quot;: 3}
print(player[0])
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> dictionaries are read by <strong>key name</strong>, not by position number.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — This should make a dictionary, but it uses the wrong brackets, so it is really a broken list.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">player = [&quot;name&quot;: &quot;Mia&quot;, &quot;level&quot;: 3]
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> a dictionary is wrapped in curly braces <code>{ }</code>, not square brackets <code>[ ]</code>.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — This should hold two facts about a pet, but a colon is missing, so it crashes.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">pet = {&quot;kind&quot; &quot;cat&quot;, &quot;age&quot;: 2}
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> every key needs a <code>:</code> between it and its value.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Explain the Code 📖</h2>
<p>Read this working dictionary carefully.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">hero = {
    &quot;name&quot;: &quot;Aria&quot;,
    &quot;hp&quot;: 100,
    &quot;weapon&quot;: &quot;bow&quot;,
}

print(f&quot;{hero['name']} has {hero['hp']} HP&quot;)
print(f&quot;Weapon: {hero['weapon']}&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>What is <code>hero</code>? How many key:value pairs does it hold?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>What does <code>hero["name"]</code> read? What about <code>hero["weapon"]</code>?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why is <code>hero["hp"]</code> clearer than remembering that HP is "the second thing" in a list?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

